<TEXT>
floodswollen rivers in texas and louisiana rushed across 
thousands of acres of normally dry land to the gulf of mexico on 
saturday and president bush made a closeup survey of the 
destruction 
some rain was forecast for parts of texas including the 
southeast where the trinity river is in record flood because of 
storms weeks ago in northern texas 
flooding and stormy weather have killed 13 people in texas two 
in illinois and one in oklahoma since april 15 and one person was 
missing in missouri thousands of people have been evacuated at 
various times in texas oklahoma arkansas and louisiana estimates 
still are being compiled on the amounts of damage to crops and 
property but it is expected to exceed hundreds of millions of 
dollars 
scattered flooding also was reported saturday in parts of iowa 
and illinois and residents cleaned up after floods in indiana and 
mississippi 
in louisiana we have one commodity ready to harvest winter 
wheat thats gone in the flooded areas said larry michaud of 
the state agriculture department there will be extensive damage 
to the cotton in the area 
the red river was returning to its banks in arkansas but 
preliminary damage estimates were rising 
heavy rain saturday caused flooding in hot springs where water 
up to 4 feet deep rushed along a downtown street police said 
store workers used sandbags to hold back the rain 
about 1000 cattle valued at 700000 drowned in arkansas 
little river county said jim barnes executive director in the 
county for the agricultural stabilization and conservation service 
damage to homes and other buildings was estimated at 15 million 
bush on a weekend visit to texas briefly visited the 
livingston dam on the trinity river in southeastern texas and flew 
over flooded areas downstream on the river northeast of houston 
this is remarkable bush told polk county judge wayne baker 
i remember it was fairly dry here not too many years ago 
the federal emergency management agency announced saturday that 
three more texas counties were declared disaster areas due to 
spring flooding bringing the total to 41 of the states 254 
counties 
flood crests moving down the trinity had forced managers of the 
livingston dam to release water through the spillways at the rate 
of 100800 cubic feet per second or 756000 gallons a second since 
thursday morning 
an estimated 7000 people living in scattered lowlying 
subdivisions downstream from the dam were warned a week earlier 
that they should evacuate 
about 100 river miles downstream at the town of liberty the 
trinity was already 5 feet over flood stage said sandra sanford a 
volunteer at the countys emergency services office 
if it rains we may have some more problems she said 
were praying we dont get any more rain storms 
they realize that the rivers still coming up but some people 
just dont want to leave she said 
in louisiana officials said the swollen red river probably has 
done most of its damage but forecasters warned farmers and 
riverfront businesses along the upper mississippi river to prepare 
for high water from storms in the midwest 
the red was expected to crest at 40 feet eight above flood 
stage sunday at alexandria in central louisiana but levees and 
floodgates protect most of area between alexandria and avoyelles 
parish where the red meets the bigger atchafalaya river officials 
said 
at least 90000 acres about 140 square miles of farmland has 
been flooded in louisiana government officials said 
the army corps of engineers had predicted that 350000 acres of 
farmland and about an equal amount of forest land would be flooded 
however corps hydrologist frankie griggs said those estimates had 
not been revised to take into account flood crests a foot lower 
than originally expected 
in western iowa more than 200 people living along perry creek 
in sioux city including 77 from a nursing home were evacuated 
early saturday because of a flash flood but were able to return 
home after sunrise the flood followed as much as 45 inches of 
rain overnight 
southern illinois braced for more storms and the prospect of 
flash flooding saturday as rivers strained to handle the runoff of 
almost 7 inches of rain in a little more than a week 
most missouri rivers were receding but the red cross said 
saturday that 208 kansas cityarea homes had been destroyed and 312 
suffered major damage 
