<TEXT>
european community foreign ministers 
on sunday laid the groundwork for closer political integration by 
1993 but made it clear that none of the 12 member nations wants a 
federal united states of europe 
irish foreign minister gerry collins described the weekend talks 
at parknasilla a lavish country resort in southwestern ireland as 
a real step forward in defining the shape of a new europe 
it is quite clear that we cannot stand still said collins 
chairman of the twoday meeting a community complacent with its 
achievements risks faltering and stagnating 
but officials said there was no question of community nations 
yielding the right to make sovereign decisions on foreign policy 
instead debate concentrated on whether more centralized powers 
should be focused on the 12 leaders of government or the 
communitys assembly the 518member european parliament based in 
strasbourg france 
britain the most skeptical about the idea of political union 
said it was pleased with the modest approach at parknasilla 
we dont want to give the euopean parliament more powers and 
we are clearly not alone said british foreign secretary douglas 
hurd 
france was adamant that foreign policy must remain a national 
matter 
today in 1990 no one is ready to delegate its sovereignty in 
foreign policy and security matters french foreign minister 
roland dumas said 
france and west germany pitched the community into an 
accelerated program for unity with a joint call last month for 
political union by 1993 
the meeting at parknasilla was the first since the community 
leaders at a summit on april 28 agreed in principle to the 
undefined frenchgerman proposal 
the foreign ministers are to meet again to complete draft 
proposals for the ecs next summit to be held in dublin at the end 
of june 
britain france and several smaller nations want the leaders of 
government to be the focus of centralized power while west 
germany backed by belgium and italy wants increased powers for 
the parliament diplomats said 
jacques delors president of the communitys strongly prounity 
executive commission based in brussels acknowledged for the first 
time there is no hope of agreement on a federation 
ireland currently holds the communitys rotating presidency 
