<TEXT>
tuberculosis a oncedeadly disease now largely 
forgotten by americans is reemerging as a health threat primarily 
among aids patients health officials said sunday 
tuberculosis cases increased 35 percent in newark nj in 1989 
over the previous year alarming health officials who had noted 
with satisfaction a slow steady decrease in tb cases over the last 
few decades 
on the national level tb cases rose 5 percent in 1989 over 
1988 a jump largely attributable to the aids crisis said dr 
philip c hopewell chief of chest service at san francisco general 
hospital 
aids attacks the bodys immune system and tb is one of the 
socalled opportunistic infections that can accompany the disease 
hopewell and other health officials discussed the link between 
aids and tb here during a fourday world conference on lung health 
which ends wednesday 
about 4 percent of americans identified as having aids also have 
been diagnosed as being infected with tuberculosis said dr dixie 
e snider jr director of the division of tuberculosis control at 
the centers for disease control in atlanta 
the american lung association estimates 20000 americans a year 
develop tb which worldwide kills an estimated 3 million persons 
each year 
in parts of africa where aids already is epidemic tuberculosis 
is also reaching those proportions said dr annik rouillon 
executive director of the international union against tuberculosis 
and lung disease in paris 
the combination of the two is really catastrophic she said 
snider stressed that tb unlike aids is curable and can be 
effectively treated even in aids patients he called for tb 
screening at drug rehabilitation programs prisons and wherever 
else aids tests are given 
he also said physicians should test for tb all persons who test 
positive for the hiv virus that causes aids 
its important we get control of the situation he said 
dr lee b reichman director of the pulmonary division of the 
university of medicine and dentistry in new jersey pointed to 
wyoming where the cdc recorded no new tb cases in 1989 as proof 
tb can still be controlled and cured 
but unlike aids tb is highly contagious and can be spread by 
airborne particles coughed up by a person with untreated 
clinically active pulmonary tb 
untreated tb kills about 50 percent of its victims within two 
years according to the cdc 
the doctors said minority groups in the united states have 
become increasingly susceptible to tb especially as the incidence 
of aids among those groups increases 
snider stressed that sustained contact is necessary for tb 
transmission although he noted that there had been an increase in 
positive tb tests among aids health workers 
tuberculosis is caused by a bacterium that commonly affects the 
lungs but can attack almost any organ for the last three decades 
it has been preventable and curable through drug therapy snider 
said 
he said an estimated 10 million to 15 million americans have 
been infected with the tb germ but only a small percentage develop 
the disease since most have immune systems strong enough to ward it 
off 
reichman noted that most americans have forgotten about the 
problems of tb the cdc says tb cases declined an average 6 percent 
a year from 1981 to 1984 
but reichman warned tb is back with a vengeance 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

