cases initiated recently against a number of kuwaiti citizens 
including former deputies of the national assembly the news 
agency quoted official sources as saying 
the arrests began may 8 when veteran opposition leader ahmed 
alkhatib and seven of his followers were detained at a diwaniya 
which is a kind of town meeting held in a private home 
the eight along with three other activists charged with 
distributing antigovernment leaflets were released three days 
later the authorities also released on bail a former parliamentary 
deputy and one other man but were still holding two members of the 
defunct parliament 
the move came in response to appeals by a number of kuwaiti 
notables who met with the emir the news agency said 
they expressed to the emir their appreciation for his paternal 
and sincere attitudes toward countrymen who though they differ on 
the method of practising democracy remain good sons and loyal 
soldiers of kuwait the agency quoted the sources as saying 
the pardon was viewed as a goodwill gesture toward the socalled 
group of 32 the activists who called for a boycott of june 10 
polling for the 75member national council they said the 
parliament was unconstitutional because the emir will appoint 25 of 
its members 
more than 80 candidates have withdrawn from the national council 
race since the nomination deadline on may 9 bringing the number of 
candidates to 485 
the emir issued a decree on april 22 setting up the chamber as a 
fouryear transitional legislature it was to assess the countrys 
parliamentary experiment and propose future steps with a view to 
averting the repetition of a third crisis 
this was a reference to the dissolution of the national assembly 
twice in a decade in 1976 and 1986 after members of parliament 
verbally attacked government ministers many of them members of the 
ruling family 
