<TEXT>
excited romanians voted sunday in 
their first free elections in 53 years and a west german exit poll 
predicted an overwhelming victory for interim president ion iliescu 
and his national salvation front 
the projection based on an exit poll of 16000 voters was 
announced on nationwide television while voters were still casting 
ballots early monday 
according to the poll iliescu won 83 percent of the votes for 
president while his challengers the national liberal partys 
radu campeanu and the national peasant partys ion ratiu won 11 
percent and six percent respectively 
in the vote for the twochamber parliament the front won a 
projected 66 percent with no other party winning more than 10 
percent the exit poll was conducted by the west german infas a 
polling group at the invitation of the government 
if the exit poll proves correct the front will not have to form 
a coalition but will be able to govern alone 
iliescu had no comment on the poll the state news agency 
rompress reported but he praised citizens for their high turnout 
and calm behavior he said foreign observers were able to see the 
virtues of sundays truly free elections 
campeanu and ratiu quickly condemned the poll 
i find the projected results exaggerated monstrously so 
they remind me of the returns in ceausescus time campeanu told 
rompress referring to communist dictator nicolae ceausescu 
i do not believe they are fair ratiu said i cannot 
imagine that 83 percent of the romanian people voted for mr 
iliescu ratiu said there were numerous instances of voter fraud 
but presented no firm evidence 
ballot counting was to begin monday and preliminary results were 
expected tuesday final returns are to be announced friday 
slowmoving lines of 200 people or more snaked out of voting 
centers on the clear windy day as voters chose an heir to the 
revolution that ousted the ironfisted ceausescu 
the almost 16 million registered voters were choosing a 
president and 506 representatives to the parliament 
at several bucharest polling stations crowds of up to 500 
waited patiently to vote after a midnight deadline for polls to 
close the original closing time of 11 pm was extended earlier in 
the evening when it became clear that the voting was proceeding 
much slower than expected especially in the capital of bucharest 
seeing this number of people willing to stand in line at this 
time of night gives me great encouragement for this democracy 
said new mexico gov garrey e carruthers leader of the us 
presidential observer delegation as he visited polling stations in 
a downtown bucharest high school 
i am voting for the first time in free romania said a 
beaming ioan hurmuzachi 67 waiting outside a bucharest polling 
center i voted in the past under ceausescu but it was very 
clear it was not real voting 
his comments appeared to reflect a universal joy among voters 
casting ballots in the first free election since 1937 
more than 80 parties ran candidates for parliament but only 
half a dozen were considered likely to win seats in the election 
which was by proportional representation 
iliescu had been heavily favored to win the presidency his 
front a loose grouping of former communists workers and 
technocrats that has dominated government since decembers 
revolution had also been expected to lead in the parliamentary 
vote 
the national peasant party and national liberal party have 
emerged as the primary opposition to the front 
but the poll by infas a respected west german institute gave 
the liberals only 95 percent to 10 percent of the parliamentary 
vote and the peasants party just 35 percent to 4 percent 
no margin of error was given 
the election was viewed internationally as a test of whether 
romanias interim government which included many former 
communists has truly embraced democracy 
some 500 foreign observers fanned out across the country to 
monitor the election which opposition parties repeatedly charged 
had been unfair due to the fronts domination of politics and media 
ratiu said before casting his ballot in bucharest that the 
runup to the election had been totally undemocratic 
campeanu also voting in the capital called the elections a 
great feat but added there is a fear they will be rigged 
romania is the only country in eastern europe to overthrow its 
communist government through a violent revolution 
although the preelection campaign occasionally turned violent 
no incidents were reported sunday 
thousands of police and soldiers were dispatched to keep order 
around polling centers 
the biggest difficulty with the vote appeared to be moving 
people through the polling stations quickly authorities said 
voters took longer than expected to fill in the complex ballots 
and there were apparently not enough voting booths 
staterun radio and television reported isolated incidents of 
prestamped ballots being discovered in bucharest and cluj it did 
not give details 
in brasov 100 miles north of bucharest some voting centers ran 
out of ballots by midafternoon the county electoral bureau 
reported voters were forced to wait while officials transferred 
extra ballots from other sites and ordered an emergency printing of 
10000 more ballots 
the officials said the situation occurred because many people 
received permission to vote outside their hometowns and cast their 
ballots in brasov 
the main issues of the campaign included moving romanias 
centralized socialist system to a freemarket economy and 
dismantling the communist system industrial workers more than 40 
percent of the labor force have strongly opposed a rapid change to 
capitalism fearing it could promote unemployment 
opposition parties have claimed iliescu will continue the 
communist system under a new name 
another issue was romanias ethnic minorities especially the 2 
million ethnic hungarians who have complained of discrimination 
tensions between romanians and ethnic hungarians exploded in march 
when six people were killed in clashes 
among those voting sunday in bucharest were ceausescus two sons 
and daughter 
the children nicu valentin and zoia elena are under 
investigation for crimes connected to their fathers 24year reign 
and the revolution nicolae ceausescu and his wife elena were 
executed after the revolution 
