president lee tenghui on sunday urged an 
end to hostilities with chinas communist government and released 
10 political prisoners to mark his inauguration 
it was the first time a taiwan president had publicly indicated 
a desire to move away from the 40yearold policy of the three 
nos toward beijing no official contact no negotiations and no 
compromise 
at his presidential inauguration ceremony lee also promised an 
amnesty for political prisoners he pledged the restoration of 
civil rights to previously jailed political prisoners including 
the chairman of the opposition democratic progressive party 
allowing them to run for public office 
nine people imprisoned on sedition charges were released sunday 
including hsu hsinliang 49 who was jailed last year after 
returning from selfimposed exile in the united states 
taiwans bestknown political prisoner shih mingteh was also 
released early monday morning he had been jailed in 1979 on 
charges of instigating an antigovernment riot in the southern port 
city of kaohsiung 
he had originally refused to allow his family to sign for his 
release because he maintains he is innocent his sister said 
human rights groups claim taiwan has roughly a dozen other 
political prisoners 
meanwhile lees nomination of the nations only fourstar 
general as premier continued to spark protests on sunday about 
10000 people including students and opposition party members 
staged a noisy march through taipei smashing windows and throwing 
eggs at offices of the military and the ruling nationalist party 
lee heads the nationalist chinese government that has been based 
on the island of taiwan ever since losing a civil war to communist 
forces on the chinese mainland in 1949 
the nationalists still claim to be the rightful government of 
all china and beijing regards taiwan as a renegade province 
lee proposed establishing channels of communication and said 
the two countries should completely open up academic cultural 
economic trade scientific and technological exchange to lay a 
foundation of mutual respect peace and prosperity 
we hope then when objective conditions are ripe we will be 
able to discuss the matter of our national reunification he 
said reunification is a longstanding goal of the nationalists 
but lee said before such relations could be established beijing 
must renounce the use of force against taiwan end its policy of 
isolating taiwan diplomatically and promote democracy and a free 
economic system in china 
while beijing previously has indicated it would not meet 
conditions set by lee the speech clearly was designed to reflect 
taipeis desire to gradually improve relations with its neighbor 
across the taiwan straits recently civilian and business contacts 
have been growing between the two sides 
the president also expressed a desire to end within two years 
the mobilization for the suppression of the communist 
rebellion which dates from 1948 the decree has ensured the 
nationalists monopoly on power by stipulating that legislators 
elected before 1949 on the chinese mainland must stay in office 
until they can return to their constituencies for reelection 
this has presented obstacles to expanding relations with china 
and introducing democratic reforms in taiwan 
lee also stressed his commitment to bring more democracy to 
taiwan but his nomination of gen hau peitsun as the new premier 
has led opposition politicians and intellectuals to question the 
governments commitment 
in recent years the nationalist party has lifted martial law 
allowed multiparty elections and eased press restrictions but 
protesters closely identify hau 71 with the partys authoritarian 
past and believe his nomination could lead to a resurgence of 
military influence 
hau was chief of the general staff for eight years before 
becoming defense minister last year 
the halfhour presidential inauguration ceremony at the sun 
yatsen memorial hall attended by about 2600 people went off 
without incident 
lee became the first native taiwanese to lead the government in 
january 1988 when he moved up from the vice presidency to succeed 
president chiang chingkuo who died in office 
chiang was the eldest son of chiang kaishek the nationalist 
leader who led the retreat to taiwan four decades ago 
