<TEXT>
the netherlands and belgium have threatened to 
contest the choice of a frenchman as head of a new development bank 
for eastern europe and the choice of london as its headquarters 
the 42 members of the 12 billion european bank for 
reconstruction and development voted late saturday to make jacques 
attali the institutions first president with london as its 
headquarters attali won over a dutch rival 
the treaty establishing the bank which will finance eastern 
europes transition to a marketoriented economy is to be signed 
in paris may 29 
as far as were concerned there was no vote it was simply an 
opinion poll said cees maas a senior dutch treasury official 
and head of the dutch delegation 
dutch delegates said they intend to review their position prior 
to the treaty signing 
there were 32 votes among the 42 founding members in favor of 
attali top aide to president francois mitterrand and credited with 
conceiving the idea of the bank his dutch rival for the chief 
executives job onno ruding received eight two of the banks 
members the european commission and the european investment bank 
abstained 
london received 23 votes as the choice for the banks 
headquarters while amsterdam and copenhagen gathered five each 
other cities in the running to host the institution were berlin 
brussels dublin ljubljana madrid prague and vienna 
it was not immediately clear whether a decision by the dutch and 
belgians not to sign the treaty would prevent the bank from coming 
to life but officials said privately that such a move certainly 
would delay the proceedings 
the dutch backed by six other small western european nations 
have led a diplomatic offensive against the choices of attali and 
london they claim the selection was a precooked decision 
cobbled together by the seven leading industrialized countries in 
washington earlier this month 
the g7 decision offended many people commented one 
european official noting that many of the smaller countries in the 
european community felt they were being left out of the 
decisionmaking process 
the 12 ec nations hold a controlling 51 percent interest in the 
bank the united states is the banks biggest single shareholder 
with a 10 percent stake eastern european countries will hold 135 
percent 
the g7 agreement on attali and london came after france and 
britain settled a longrunning dispute over their respective 
rankings inside the international monetary fund that arrangement 
gives france equal ranking with britain 
observers at the time said the deal was a tradeoff with 
britain agreeing to the imf reclassification if france would 
support london as the site of the development bank 
