<TEXT>
the washington public power supply system 
has announced it will offer 600 million in refunding bonds for 
sale the week of june 4 
the sale announced friday would be the fourth in the effort by 
wppss and the federal bonneville power administration to refinance 
about 28 billion in bonds sold a decade ago to finance 
construction of three nuclear power plants the outstanding 
highinterest bonds carry interest rates upwards of 9 percent 
about 16 billion in debt for wppss plants nos 1 2 and 3 has 
been refinanced through issuance of new bonds carrying interest 
rates of from 6 percent to 7 percent 
wppss spokesman john britton said friday there will be at least 
one and possibly two more sales after june he said all sales of 
refinancing bonds are to be completed this year 
it has been estimated that the refinancing effort will save the 
northwest region which is paying for the wppss plants through bpa 
electricity rates about 1 billion 
preston michie assistant general counsel with bonneville said 
it was hoped the bonds sold in june would be at about the range of 
interest rates received in the previous three sales 
previous sales were in october and december 1989 and in march of 
this year 
senior manager for the june sale is first boston corp 
the supply system headquartered in richland attempted to build 
five nuclear power plants in the 1970s 
of those one plant no 2 at the hanford nuclear reservation 
is operating after starting up in late 1984 
two others nos 1 and 3 are mothballed because of construction 
delays 
wppss terminated the other two plants nos 4 and 5 in 1982 
and defaulted on 225 billion in bonds sold for their construction 
plants 1 2 and 3 are being paid for through bpa rates the 
bonneville umbrella was never extended to plants nos 4 and 5 
</TEXT>
